## 0.2 Properties of Amino acids

* Amino acids are amphoteric because they contain a basic group (amino group which can accept H+) and an acidic group (carboxyl group which can donate H+) (Figure 3).
* Amino acids are soluble in water and ionise to form zwitterions, ions with both positive and negative charges (Figure 3).
* The amino group receives an H+ and becomes positively-charged.
* The carboxyl group dissociates, releasing H+ and becomes negatively-charged.
* Due to their amphoteric property, amino acids can resist slight pH changes, thus serving as pH buffers (Figure 3). A buffer minimises changes in pH when a small amount of acid or alkali is added to it. Such property is essential in biological system where any sudden change in pH could adversely affect the performance of proteins like enzymes.

